	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Doh!  In defense of enchanters everywhere, and masters of any trade skill, a note on player-crafted items.  I understand that you are too lazy to actually read any information on the actual trade skills required to craft the items whose prices you have such a good time moaning about.  Here's a primer for you:<BR>
<BR>
Yes, the typical markup for player-crafted items is 100%.  Less for lower-level items, more (and much more) for high-level items.  I'll sell stacks of dmg 3 range 150 arrows for the price of materials + 50%, until they become trivial to me, then I'll drop it down to very close to cost.  Because I have very little to gain from it, and nothing whatsoever to lose, why not take it easy on a noobie's pocketbook?<BR>
<BR>
If I'm making damage 6 range 150 arrows, you'd better believe that I'm marking them up a *full* 100%.  This is because even if my fail rate is only 35 or 40%, every failure HURTS.  At times my failure rate will creep perilously close to 50%, meaning that a 100% markup gets me NO PROFIT.  Shaped darkwood compound bows cost in the neighborhood of 340pp per attempt, but most fletchers sell them for 1000 to 1200pp.  Three failures is in a row is certainly not unheard of with a non-trivial item, and this bow NEVER becomes trivial.  <BR>
<BR>
Also, and perhaps more importantly, players have absolute control over the price of player-crafted only items.  Meaning I can ask as much as I want, as long as there is someone out there who is willing to pay it.  We have the monopoly, and we are quite rare.  If you don't want my bows badly enough, you won't be willing to pay my outlandish prices.  Fact of life.  And I don't really care, because there is always someone out there who will.<BR>
<BR>
Regarding jewelcraft, in an attempt to drift somewhat nearer the topic of azure ruby rings, jewellers have just as much to lose in a single attempt at high levels.  Enchanters also have the sole ability to create enchanted metals, which alone requires a high experience level, as well as the pith to make it to Neriak for the necessary spell(s).  Big risk, lots of hard work, very few willing to do it, results in a monopoly.  Same type of situation.<BR>
<BR>
So don't rag on prices.  Either pay them, or shut up.  Don't just piss and moan without purpose.<BR>
<BR>
&lt;big smile&gt;<BR>
<BR>
Have an elfie day.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
